page.title: 09ANIMALS OF WYCHWOOD FOREST
page.content: {Fallow deer}have roamed this area since before 1086. There were 1000 head recorded by Parliament in 1792.Numbers dropped after disafforestation from 1860,when about half the trees were felled. Today their numbers are kept within reasonable bounds by culling,to reduce destruction of woodland trees and plants. Many a {King }has dined on { {venison }from Whychwood. In the forest they are unmanaged and considered { {vermin.}Other mammals include { {rabbits,hares,and grey squirrels. {Grass snakes,}once abundant are { {rarely}seen,and no{adders }have ever been reported in the forest. A recent{ {invasion}has been the {Muntjac }(a Chinese water deer).
